==Old English==

===Etymology===
From an Indo-European root ''*(s)kel-'' ‘shall, must, owe’.  Cognate with Old High German [[scolan]] (German [[sollen]]), Old Saxon [[skulan]] (Dutch [[zullen]]), Old Norse [[skulu]] (Swedish [[skola]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌺𐌿𐌻𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'ʃʊlan/

===Verb===
'''sculan''' (preterite-present: '''sceal''' ‘he owes’, '''sculon''' ‘they owe’, '''sceolde''' ‘he owed’)
====Transitive====
# to [[owe]]
====Auxiliary====
# to be obliged, [[must]], [[should]]
# [[should]], [[shall]], expressing the speaker’s intention
#:''Þa cwæð he: Hwæt sceal ic singan?'': then he said, ‘what shall I sing?’  (Bede)
# [[shall]], to be going or about (to do something)

